s the Tokyo Olympics provided another impulse for discussions about sexual minority rights. As a result, recent surveys show a dramatic increase in the acceptance of same-sex marriage. However, Japan is the only G7 country that does not recognize same-sex partnerships and sexual minorities are not legally protected from discrimination. This is due to deeply rooted traditional and religiously tainted family values, represented and perpetuated by post-war Japan's deeply conservative political establishment. While LGBTQ+ issues in Japan have received scholarly attention since the 1990s, there is little scholarship in English on developments after 2000, let alone in the form of anthologies. This volume will bridge this gap by shedding light on political and cultural representations of and by sexual minorities in Japan after 2000, making, thus, available in English a completely novel perspective on LGBTQ+ issues in Japan and East Asia.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSex rolezJapan2DLC. 0aSex rolezJapan. 0aSexual minoritieszJapan2DLC. 0aSexual minoritieszJapan. 4aGeschlechterrolle. 4aJapan. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aLGBT. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aJapan.  aLGBTQ+.  agender identiy.1 aFukunaga, Genya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamano, Saori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawasaka, Kazuyoshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawasaka, Kazuyoshi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKhor, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKubo, Yuta